title: Development of an Indigenous Intellectual Property Toolkit for the Cultural Ministers  Council
desc: A project to raise awareness about  Indigenous Intellectual Property has been developed by the Cultural Ministers   Council, as part of the Council of Australian Governments  (COAG)  Reconciliation Framework. The project recognises Indigenous people as the  custodians of their cultural heritage and promotes greater respect and  responsibility in the dissemination of Indigenous stories, art works and  cultural knowledge. The project will educate people about copyright and moral  rights that apply to the publication and reproduction of Indigenous cultural  expressions. It will also improve understandings between commercial business  operators and Indigenous communities.
text: Development of an Indigenous Intellectual Property Toolkit for the Cultural Ministers  Council.        A project to raise awareness about  Indigenous Intellectual Property has been developed by the Cultural Ministers   Council, as part of the Council of Australian Governments  (COAG)  Reconciliation Framework. The project recognises Indigenous people as the  custodians of their cultural heritage and promotes greater respect and  responsibility in the dissemination of Indigenous stories, art works and  cultural knowledge. The project will educate people about copyright and moral  rights that apply to the publication and reproduction of Indigenous cultural  expressions. It will also improve understandings between commercial business  operators and Indigenous communities.

title: Provision of Jobwise Outreach SelfHelp Groups
desc: The Department of Employment and Workplace Relations (the Department) is seeking proposals from organisations to establish and facilitate in selected regions Jobwise Outreach Self Help Groups ( the Self Help Groups ) targeted at people aged 45 years or over who are not eligible for the full range of Job Network services.    Increasing participation rates for mature age people in the Australian workforce, given the ageing of the population, is one of the most significant economic and social challenges of the next decade.  The Self Help Groups are part of the Australian Government s strategy to improve participation rates for mature age people in the Australian workforce.      The Self Help Groups are also a means of assisting mature age people to better connect to existing relevant programmes and services within their local area.

title: RFT for a Panel to Provide (1) Benchmarking of ICT Services (non-outsourced) and (2) Strategic ICT Services.
desc: The Tax Office is seeking to establish a panel of providers capable of helping it determine how it s spending on ICT (excluding outsourced services) and the services it offers compares to other similar sized and natured, public and private organisations. This will be established through a series of benchmarking activities carried out on the services delivered by ICT (referred to as Tier 1 services) over a term of 3 to 6 years. This will include an ongoing annual benchmarking exercise to monitor performance over a period of time. Additional strategic ICT services (referred to as Tier 2 services) will be required to provide advice on improving efficiency and service delivery in areas identified by the Tier 1 services.

title: National Delivery of Train-the-Trainer Training for Age Management Training
desc: The Department of Employment and Workplace Relations is seeking to engage a provider for the national delivery of train-the-trainer training for Age Management Training to qualified trainers over the 2006-07 financial year.     The objectives of Age Management Training are to raise awareness of Australia`s ageing population and promote an age balanced workforce by assisting organisations implement policies and practices to increase their attraction and retention of mature age workers, and to help experienced workers plan and implement a phased retirement.      The Department has developed Age Management Training materials for Team Leader and Experienced Worker programmes.      Training for Age Management Training is to familiarise qualified trainers with mature age employment issues and the Department`s Age Management Training course materials, answer any questions participants might have, and assess and accredit participants to deliver Age Management Training to Clients.      The successful tenderer will deliver train-the-trainer training and accreditation for the Department`s Age Management Training to qualified trainers in metropolitan and regional areas of all States and Territories to enable them to present the Team Leader and Experienced Worker workshops to peak bodies, businesses and other interested organisations, workplaces, and individual workers, jobseekers and retirees.    The Department`s required outcome is to create a pool of motivated and accredited trainers across Australia that are able to deliver Age Management Training to clients.

title: National Adviser Network Programme
desc: On 28 April 2006, the Minister for Employment and Workplace Relations launched the Unlawful Termination Assistance Scheme (UTAS). The Scheme provides financial assistance to eligible terminated employees to seek legal advice as to the merits of their unlawful termination claim, to assist them in making an informed decision about whether to commence further legal proceedings.               To compliment this assistance, the Minister also announced the development of a best practice education and training programme on fair and proper employment termination practices. This programme would assist employers and employees in their understanding of their rights and obligations under the unfair dismissal and unlawful termination provisions of the Workplace Relations Act 1996 (the Act).               The Department of Employment and Workplace Relations (DEWR) is undertaking a competitive tender process to purchase services for the development of a national advisory network to deliver information and advice to employers and employees about their rights and obligations under the unfair dismissal and unlawful termination provisions of the Act. A key focus of the tender will be the advocating of good management practices to support better practice in the workplace. The objectives of the National Advisor Network Programme (the Programme) are to:                  increase employers understanding of good management practices relating to hiring, performance management and conflict resolution;                     provide employers with an understanding of fair and proper employment termination practices, leading to reduced unfair dismissal and unlawful termination claims; and                     provide employers with information and advice about the unfair dismissal and unlawful termination provisions of the Act, leading to greater understanding of and compliance with their legal obligations under the Act;                  o  informative materials should also be developed for employers to provide to their employees concerning employee rights under the Act.

title: Wise Workforce Programme 2006-07
desc: The Department of Employment and Workplace Relations (the Department) is seeking proposals from organisations to provide the Wise Workforce Programme (the Programme) in specified Regions of Australia for the 2006-07 financial year.     The objectives of the Programme are to assist employers to:  1.  understand the value of Mature Age workers and Australia`s workforce demographics;  2.  appreciate the advantages of developing age positive workplace policies and practices for sustainable business growth; and   3. develop their own age positive workplace policies and practices.    The Programme is delivered in ten Regions nationally each year.    The successful tenderer will deliver:  1. Awareness  Providers will be required to raise awareness of:   (a) workforce ageing and its implications,   (b) the value of Mature Age workers,   (c) the advantages of age positive workplace policies and practices for recruitment and retention, and  (d) the ease with which age positive workplace policies and practices can be implemented in workplaces within Industry Sectors in the specified Regions  by marketing the Programme and its messages to Participants.   2. text: Wise Workforce Programme 2006-07.The Department of Employment and Workplace Relations (the Department) is seeking proposals from organisations to provide the Wise Workforce Programme (the Programme) in specified Regions of Australia for the 2006-07 financial year.     The objectives of the Programme are to assist employers to:  1.  understand the value of Mature Age workers and Australia`s workforce demographics;  2.  appreciate the advantages of developing age positive workplace policies and practices for sustainable business growth; and   3. develop their own age positive workplace policies and practices.    The Programme is delivered in ten Regions nationally each year.    The successful tenderer will deliver:  1. Awareness  Providers will be required to raise awareness of:   (a) workforce ageing and its implications,   (b) the value of Mature Age workers,   (c) the advantages of age positive workplace policies and practices for recruitment and retention, and  (d) the ease with which age positive workplace policies and practices can be implemented in workplaces within Industry Sectors in the specified Regions  by marketing the Programme and its messages to Participants.   2. Assistance  The Provider will be required to provide assistance to Participants to implement age positive workplace policies and practices.    The Provider will be required to deliver the programme to Participants including businesses, employers, peak bodies and other organisations, government, and employment service providers from the Industry Sectors relevant to each Region.

title: Provision of Jobwise Outreach Mature Age Workshops and Self Help Groups
desc: The Department of Employment and Workplace Relations (the Department) is seeking proposals from organisations to establish and facilitate in selected regions Jobwise Outreach Mature Age Workshops and Self Help Groups (`the Self Help Groups`) targeted at people aged 45 years or over who are not eligible for the full range of Job Network services.    Increasing participation rates for mature age people in the Australian workforce, given the ageing of the population, is one of the most significant economic and social challenges of the next decade.      The Mature Age Workshops and Self Help Groups are part of the Australian Government`s strategy to improve participation rates for mature age people in the Australian workforce.    The Mature Age Workshops and Self Help Groups are a means of assisting mature age people to better connect to existing relevant programmes and services within their local area.

title: Structured Training and Employment Projects (STEP) Employment and Related Services Panel of Contractors
desc: The Department of Employment and Workplace Relations (the Department) is seeking to establish a panel of organisations (`the Panel`) to deliver Structured Training and Employment Projects (STEP) Employment and Related Services (STEP ERS) to Employers in labour market regions throughout Australia (`the Services`).     The Panel will  provide sustainable employment for Indigenous Australians by providing Employers with one or more of the following Services:         pre-employment support services that may include the provision of training and the development and implementation of recruitment strategies;        employment placement services to assist them place and retain Indigenous Australians in their workplaces; and        mentoring services to help them retain their Indigenous Australian employees.      The Services aim to provide sustainable employment for Indigenous Australians throughout Australia, particularly in the private sector and to equip Employers with the skills, knowledge and expertise necessary to continue to provide sustainable employment opportunities for Indigenous Australians in their organisations without the need for ongoing assistance from a Panel Member.

Other responsibilities include demolition and disposal, the excavation of contaminated soils, the sourcing and placement of backfill and the construction and eventual disposal of biopiles.

title: Structured Training and Employment Projects Employment and Related Services (STEP ERS) Panel
desc: The Department of Employment and Workplace Relations (the Department) is seeking to expand the panel of organisations (the Panel) to deliver Structured Training and Employment Projects Employment and Related Services (STEP ERS) to Employers in labour market regions throughout Australia (the Services).     In 2006 the Australian Government Department of Employment and Workplace Relations approached the market (RFT 2006/22) to establish the Panel.  Approximately 60 organisations were selected to join the Panel to deliver Services across Australia.  Demand for delivery of STEP ERS by brokers is expected to expand, particularly with the cessation of Community Development Employment Projects (CDEP) services in urban and major regional areas from 1 July 2007.  The Department is approaching the market to provide organisations interested in being engaged as a member of the existing Panel with an opportunity to become members of that Panel.      Current Panel members may decide to re-tender:  . the LMRs where it provides services;   . to target particular industry sectors;   . to target particular clients? industry sectors; or  . to increase the number of services it wishes to deliver.     The Panel will provide sustainable employment for Indigenous Australians by providing Employers with one or more of the following Services:  . pre-employment support services that may include the provision of training and the development and implementation of recruitment strategies;   . employment placement services to assist them place and retain Indigenous Australians in their workplaces; and   . mentoring services to help them retain their Indigenous Australian employees    The Services aim to provide sustainable employment for Indigenous Australians throughout Australia, particularly in the private sector and to equip Employers with the skills, knowledge and expertise necessary to continue to provide sustainable employment opportunities for Indigenous Australians in their organisations without the need for ongoing assistance from a Panel Member.

title: Provision of offshore skills assessment services for potential skilled migrants to Australia.
desc: Trades Recognition Australia (TRA), within the Department of Employment and Workplace Relations (the Department), is seeking tenders from Australian Registered Training Organisations (RTOs) with the relevant scope of registration to deliver skills assessment services in the United Kingdom, Sri Lanka, South Africa, India and the Philippines for potential skilled migrants seeking skills recognition as motor mechanics; general plumbers; refrigeration and air conditioning mechanics; general electricians; cable jointers; electrical powerline tradespersons; bricklayers; and carpenters and joiners.    The successful Tenderer(s) must be able to provide a fair, practical, relevant, accurate, time efficient and affordable assessment service for potential skilled migrants.    Successful Tenderers will be required to enter into a Deed for the Provision of Offshore Skills Assessment Services (the Deed) with the Commonwealth. The Deed will have an initial term of three years commencing on 1 July 2007, with the possibility of an extension to five years.

desc: The Department of Communications, Information Technology and the Arts invites your organisation to submit a proposal to undertake a study and provide a written report analysing the cultural and creative sectorýs technical capability in the digital environment.    On behalf of Cultural Ministers Council (CMC), the Department has convened a ýRoundtableý of officials from the Australian Government, all Australian States and Territories as well as New Zealand to undertake a mapping exercise identifying opportunities to strengthen the prospects for the creative sector in the digital environment. The Department is providing secretariat support to the Roundtable and is currently gathering information from a variety of sources, for a policy based mapping exercise. More information is at www.culture.gov.au/cmcroundtable/. title: Courses for the Australian Government Summer School for Teachers Programme
desc: Request for Expressions of Interest – Course Development and Delivery for the Australian Government Summer Schools for Teachers programmeThe Australian Government will run the first Australian Government Summer Schools for Teachers in January 2008. This fully funded, 10-day residential programme will provide high quality knowledge and skills for teachers in the key priority areas of Literacy and Numeracy, English, Mathematics, Science and Australian History.Interested organisations, including consortia involving universities, professional associations, private providers and educators are now invited to submit expressions of interest to develop and deliver research-based and targeted courses for this programme. These courses are to be run at various sites across Australia.  Applicants can submit proposals to deliver courses covering individual priority areas, or all priorities.A subsequent Request for Tender process may be conducted, drawing from parties who have expressed interest via this current process. The first Summer Schools will run in January 2008.

title: Evaluation of the Enterprise Learning for the 21st Century and Step to the Future Initiatives.
desc: A two-phase evaluation of the Department of Education, Science and Training s (DEST) Enterprise Learning of the 21st Century initiative and Step to the Future Youth Forums sponsored in part by DEST, is being undertaken.  Phase One is to evaluate the success of EL21 projects in meeting the initiative s strategic priorities; to benchmark projects against best practice as identified in the Literature Review on Enterprise Education; to develop an Action Plan for the future direction of enterprise education in Australia; and to evaluate the resources developed by the EL21 projects. title: A Professional Learning Package for Teachers on Consumer and Financial Literacy Education
desc: The Department of Education, Science and Training  (in cooperation with the Australian Government Treasury) is seeking tenders from interested organisations or consortia who are suitably experienced and qualified to develop a creative and contemporary National Consumer and Financial Literacy Professional Learning Package.  The Package will provide teachers with the knowledge and skills required to deliver consumer and financial literacy learning for students in accordance with the National Goals of Schooling.  The Package will be shaped by the Ministerial Council on Education, Employment, Training and Youth Affairs  (MCEETYA) Consumer and Financial Literacy Framework  and will support school leaders and teachers in implementing the dimensions of learning identified in the Framework across the curriculum.  The Package is to be based on leading practice principles of professional learning.

title: Structured Training and Employment Projects Employment and Related Services (STEP ERS) Panel Northern Territory Only
desc: In order to effectively and efficiently implement the Government s Emergency Response in the Northern Territory, the Department is approaching the market to expand the Structured Training and Employment Projects Employment and Related Services (STEP ERS) Panel ( the Panel ) in respect of the Northern Territory Labour Market Region.  As part of the Australian Government s Northern Territory emergency response, the Community Development Employment Projects (CDEP) programme in the Northern Territory will progressively be replaced with real jobs, training and mainstream employment programmes. This will occur on a community by community basis from September 2007.  CDEP will not be funded in the Northern Territory after 30 June 2008. The Panel will provide sustainable employment for Indigenous Australians by providing Employers with one or more of the following Services:pre-employment support services that may include the provision of training and the development and implementation of recruitment strategies; employment placement services to assist them place and retain Indigenous Australians in their workplaces; and mentoring services to help them retain their Indigenous Australian employees. The aim of STEP ERS is to provide sustainable employment for Indigenous Australians and to equip Employers with the skills, knowledge and expertise necessary to continue to provide sustainable employment opportunities for Indigenous Australians in their organisations without the need for ongoing assistance from a Panel Member.

title: Strategies to address the international recognition of Australian VET qualifications
desc: This project will identify and research the key issues associated with the recognition of Australian vocational education and technical (VET) qualifications in the international environment.  The study will provide detailed information on where complementarities exist, specify potential barriers to recognition, and make recommendations on possible initiatives for cooperative action to eliminate or ameliorate those issues.

title: National Service Coordinator for An Even Start ? National Tuition Programme
desc: Procurement for services of a National Service Coordinator to administer the delivery of tuition through private providers to students eligible for assistance under  An Even Start – National Tuition Programme  across all Australian States and Territories.  The National Service Coordinator will be responsible for the management of private tuition arrangements to eligible students by private tutors (individuals and private tuition companies).The successful tenderer will be responsible for the facilitation of the tuition arrangements of eligible students only where their parents have requested that tuition be conducted by a private tutor rather than school based arrangements.  The National Service Coordinator will:·         engage and pay private tuition providers; ·         facilitate the provision of tuition to eligible students; ·         ensure private tutors deliver tuition in accordance with Programme Guidelines, and the Tutor Code of Conduct; ·         provide reports to the Department as required; and engage with key stakeholders.

title: Evaluation of the outcomes of COAG s recommendations on mutual recognition of occupational licensing
desc: The COAG Skills Recognition Steering Committee (the Steering Committee) through DEST is seeking a consultant to undertake a formative evaluation of the outcomes of the Council of Australian Governments  (COAG) decision on full and effective mutual recognition of occupational licences across Australia.  As part of a broad package of initiatives to address skills shortages, COAG agreed, at its meeting on 10 February 2006, to implement a national approach to skills recognition for occupational licencing.  This decision was intended to assist in achieving a more mobile workforce to meet skills needs.  The formative evaluation which is the subject of this Request for Tender will be of the implementation of COAG s decision in so far as it relates to: a) achieving full and effective mutual recognition arrangements across states and territories of vocationally trained licensed occupations; b) improving regulator confidence in vocational training system outcomes so that regulators will recognise vocational education and training qualifications as meeting all skill related requirements for an occupational licence; andc) ensuring regulators will grant a licence to migrants from key source countries in priority skills shortage trades who have had their qualifications recognised through a new streamlined assessment system overseas so they can work as soon as they reach Australia.The objective will be to assess and provide advice to the Steering Committee on:a) the effectiveness of the skills recognition project;b) the sustainability of project outcomes; andc) successful implementation of remaining components of the project.

title: Assist the AER to assess Transend s revenue proposal
desc: The Australian Energy Regulator (AER) is to conduct an assessment into the appropriate revenue determination to apply to prescribed transmission services provided by the Tasmanian electricity network business Transend for the period from 1 July 2009 to 30 June 2014.  This review will place in accordance with the National Electricity Rules (NER), particularly chapter 6A.  The AER requires an appropriately qualified consultant to assist the AER and to review Transend s past and forecast capital expenditure (capex), operational expenditure (opex) and service standards proposals.The consultant s review will assist the AER to assess Transend s revenue proposal relative to the requirements of the NER. In accordance with the NER, the consultant s report will be published in support of the AER s decision. The AER is required to release its draft decision by 30 November 2008. The consultant s final report must be provided to the AER no later than 30 September 2008.

title: Develop and deliver Defence and Strategic Policy Seminars for Defence Graduate programs
desc: The Strategy Coordination and Governance Executive requires the provision of services to develop and deliver Defence and Strategic Policy seminars for Defence Graduate programs.The aim is to provide Defence graduates with the necessary knowledge to deliver high quality strategic policy advice.  The seminars should explain the progression of Australian defence policy and provide participants with a solid grounding in historical and current policy rationale and debates.  The seminars should focus on defence policy as a public policy discipline involved in providing practical answers to real questions.  The seminars should also explain how Defence fits into the broader political and government policy environment.

title: Provision of academic and support services for the Public Sector Management Program
desc: The PSM Program is an established national middle management development strategy initiated by the public sector in 1989. The Program is a partnership between Commonwealth, State/Territory and Local Governments. The Program is overseen by a National Board, made up of representatives from all jurisdictions, (the Partners). The Board is supported by a National Secretariat located at the Australian Public Service Commission. Under the current model, the Program acquires accreditation and support services from four universities, a College of Moderators and a pool of assessors, with each contributing to the PSM Program. The current deeds of agreement for the provision of the PSM Program accreditation services from the four universities are due to expire. The Australian Public Service Commission is facilitating this procurement process on behalf of all Partners.

title: Natural Resource Management Services
desc: The Harbour Trust requires the services of a natural resources manager to implement the North Head Operational Plan (2007).  The primary outcome under the Management Plan for the Former School of Artillery at North Head is  an opportunity for the creation of a sanctuary in a metropolis of 4 million people .The key objectives of the North Head Operational Plan are:to establish a wildlife sanctuary at North Head in co-operation with other landholders and stakeholdersto re-establish some of the wildlife that has disappeared from North Headto support Harbour Trust activities which engage the Australian community in the sanctuary and which provide an opportunity for people to reconnect with nature and to participate in the restoration of habitats and wildlife populationsto undertake scientific research on issues relevant to the conservation for native wildlife and habitats, particularly the restoration of habitats in an urban setting.The Harbour Trust intends to implement of an active conservation and land management strategy on the natural resources site.

The purpose of the study is to better understand employment outcomes for graduates, pathways to achieving these outcomes and links to secondary school and transition experiences.  Of particular interest is how employment outcomes vary by student, course and institution characteristics.  Research findings will be used to better understand graduate supply issues and inform policy development.

title: The impact of English language proficiency and workplace readiness on employment outcomes and performance of tertiary international students
desc: The impact of English language proficiency and workplace readiness on employment outcomes and performance of tertiary international students.The aim of this project is to develop a body of knowledge and effective strategies that will support the Department s efforts to build the capacity of providers to enhance English language proficiency and workplace readiness of international students, thereby improving their graduate employment outcomes and enhancing international education s potential as a valuable source of skill development for the Australian economy.To date, no comprehensive review has been undertaken of information available on the impact of English language proficiency and workplace readiness on the performance and outcomes of international students who enter the Australian workplace after completion of their studies.

title: Provision of academic and support services for the Public Sector Management Program
desc: The PSM Program is an established national middle management development strategy initiated by the public sector in 1989. The Program is a partnership between Commonwealth, State/Territory and Local Governments. The Program is overseen by a National Board, made up of representatives from all jurisdictions, (the Partners). The Board is supported by a National Secretariat located at the Australian Public Service Commission. The Program acquires accreditation and support services from universities as described in the RFT documentation.  The Australian Public Service Commission is facilitating this procurement process on behalf of all Partners.

title: 2009 to 2011 Endeavour Awards Selection Panel Tender
desc: The Endeavour Awards is the Australian Government s internationally competitive, merit-based scholarship program providing opportunities for citizens of the Asia-Pacific and the Middle East to undertake study, research and professional development in Australia. Awards are also available for Australians to do the same abroad. A smaller number of awards are available for participants from Europe and the Americas.The Department requires panels of academics and professionals from a diversity of fields of study and professional backgrounds and institutions, with an understanding of the challenges and value of international learning, research and professional development experiences. During September 2008 the Department will hold selection panels to rank applications for the 2009 Endeavour Awards. Panel members will be required to rank applications online through the Endeavour Panel Assessment System and attend a panel meeting in Canberra. The Department will remunerate panel members for the ranking of applications and selection panel meeting days. This process will occur annually over an initial three year period.

title: The Provision of Consultancy Services for the Method and Basis of the Setting of the Import Parity Price (IPP) for Unleaded Petrol and Diesel in Australia (IPP Consultancy).
desc: The Australian fuel industry assesses the value of refined petrol and diesel products to be the Import Parity Price (IPP), as this represents the only economically valid outcome as the products are internationally traded.  An IPP is translated into a domestic price by assuming that the same product was purchased in the nearest major market (Singapore), and then transported to Australia, and delivered into a local storage facility.

title: Review of the National Safe Schools Framework
desc: The National Safe Schools Framework (NSSF) was developed in 2002 and endorsed by all Ministers for Education in 2003. The NSSF provides a national approach to safe school practices. It consists of a set of nationally agreed principles for safe and supportive school environments and includes appropriate responses which schools can adopt to address the issues of bullying, harassment, violence, and child abuse and neglect.Since the NSSF s inception, there have been significant developments in technology which has seen the scope of bullying activities widen to include the use of technology such as mobile phones and computers to bully victims both inside and outside of school hours (known as cyber-bullying).The aim of this project is to review the current NSSF and supporting documentation to incorporate changes in technology, legislation and government policy. This will ensure the NSSF remains a valuable resource for schools.

This will ensure the NSSF remains a valuable resource for schools.

title: Health Data Collection, analysis and reporting in Respect to Cancer
desc: Cancer Australia is keen to ensure a nationally consistent approach to clinical cancer data collection and reporting that will facilitate comparative analysis and benchmarking nationally of cancer outcomes across Australia, with the overall aim of improving outcomes for all people with cancer.Organisations with expertise in clinical cancer data management and reporting are invited to apply for: A) the establishment of a standing offer arrangement with one or more suppliers for a period of 2 years to provide these services on a non-exclusive basis;   B) the delivery of an initial Gynaecological cancers data management project for improved clinical outcomes and benchmarking for the National Centre for Gynaecological Cancers that will be undertaken in partnership with National Breast and Ovarian Cancer Centre to: There are two elements to this project:    1.  Coordinate the pilot testing of a developed specialist clinical national minimum data set for gynaecological cancers; and    2.   Undertake a brief scoping study of existing resources available for the collection of surgical synoptic data for gynaecological cancers at point of care .  Tenderer/s may apply for one or both elements of this initial project

desc: The Murray-Darling Basin Authority (MDBA) is developing a Plan for the long-term management of the Murray-Darling Basin.    This will require extensive consultation with stakeholders, including the community.  Consultation will take traditional forms – such as town hall meetings, and shopfronts, as well as new innovative social media forms, such as online forums.   We are seeking the services of a professional, experienced company to develop a range of forums to enhance our online engagement with our stakeholders.    In addition, we required that the successful tenderer be able to support the engagement through the provision of contact services (moderating and responding to web activities) and answering calls to our hotline number.   Development of online forums will commence as soon as the contract commences, and the support services will be required during our public consultation period (four months commencing in mid 2010).

category: Natural resources management or conservation strategy planning services
title: Assessment of current and potential risks to the quantity and quality of the Murray-Darling Basin s water resources
desc: The MDBA s NRM Division is currently seeking to commission a range of studies to better understand the impacts of risks to the quantity and quality of water resources of the Basin.  These projects are broadly grouped as:1. Studies on risks driven by climate change 2. Studies on risks relating to catchment processes 3. Studies on risks arising from direct water interception and use, and4. Case studies and development of methods and tools to address the above.The risk assessments will inform the development of better management strategies by anticipating the impacts of these risks, the likelihood of their occurrence and their consequences.Expressions of Interest are sought from service providers with expertise in the areas of investigation listed above.  Detailed project briefs for the individual projects are currently being developed and service providers who are shortlisted will be invited to submit proposals for all or some of these projects.

title: Scholarships PNG
desc: Four primary scholarship programs will be supported by this tender: the Australian Development Scholarships which is targeted to PNG s priority human resource and development needs through full time postgraduate and undergraduate study in Australia; the Australian Leadership Awards to develop leadership and build linkages within the Asia-Pacific; and the NZ Development Scholarships-Public and NZ Development Scholarships-Open Categories both seeking to strengthen PNG s human resource base by supporting identified priority areas. The services include scholarship promotion and selection, placement of students into Australian and New Zealand universities, and assisting students returning to PNG.

title: Business Analyst/Data Modeller
desc: The Commonwealth represented by and acting through the Australian Taxation Office (Tax Office), invites Tenders for the provision of suitably qualified personnel (Specified Personnel) to work at the Tax Office s Canberra premises. Standard Business Reporting (SBR) is a Treasury led multi-agency initiative that aims to reduce the reporting burden on Australian businesses.The Tax Office SBR project has merged both the Business Solutions (BSol) and Office of the Chief Knowledge (OCKO) sections of the Tax Office for this project to gain economies of scale, skills transfer and increase succession and contingency planning. To ensure the timely delivery of the project there is a requirement for a number of Specified Personnel to perform the role of Business Analyst/Data Modellers.The positions are located in Canberra to deliver the Tax Office agency contribution to the SBR program and require a Highly Protected Security Clearance.This new process is a result of the Tax Office being unable to secure sufficient numbers of Specified Personnel with the required levels of skill and experience from RFT 044-2009.

title: Market Development Facility (MDF)
desc: AusAID has designed a Market Development Facility (MDF) to implement market development activities in Fiji and Timor Leste. The Facility is underpinned by a market-based approach that aims to make markets more competitive and accessible to poor men and women, enabling them to find their own way out of poverty. It seeks to leverage systemic change in how markets work, thereby offering the potential for pro-poor impact at significant scale. The market-based approach will be implemented by a Contractor based on an approved proposal to implement the design, aimed at identifying market failures and opportunities, and facilitating changes to address these through appropriate interventions. The intention is for the Facility to support market development programs in other countries in due course.

title: Australia s Education Partnership with Indonesia – AusAID Performance Oversight and Monitoring
desc: The Governments of Australia and Indonesia are entering into a new AUD500m Education Partnership with Indonesia. The Partnership will focus on four components: school construction, school and district management, Islamic school accreditation, and the Analytical and Capacity Development Partnership. The Education Partnership is Australia s contribution to Indonesia s Education Sector Support Program, which is also co-financed by the European Union.   The AusAID Performance Oversight and Monitoring Contractor will operate across the four components of the Education Partnership and will be responsible for monitoring the impact of Australia s investment in Indonesia s education sector.

title: Australia s Education Partnership with Indonesia – School Systems and Quality
desc: The Governments of Australia and Indonesia are entering into a new AUD500m Education Partnership with Indonesia. The Partnership will focus on four components: school construction, school and district management, Islamic school accreditation, and the Analytical and Capacity Development Partnership. The Education Partnership is Australia s contribution to Indonesia s Education Sector Support Program, which is also co-financed by the European Union.  The School Systems and Quality (SSQ) Contractor will provide technical assistance to the Government of Indonesia to support school-based management of Australian-funded schools and to enhance national and subnational government management of schools funded by both Australia and Indonesia. The Contractor will be responsible for supporting the development of a nationwide accredited training system for principals, school supervisors and local government education officials. In addition to these services, the Contractor will support the accreditation of Islamic schools, and manage block grants to Islamic schools and designated accreditation support entities.

title: Poverty Reduction Support Facility
desc: Indonesia: Poverty Reduction Support Facility: management services to support the Vice-Presidential National Team.The Poverty Reduction Support Facility (the Facility) aims to support the National Team for Accelerating Poverty Reduction (Tim Nasional Percepatan Penanggulangan Kemiskinan) and assist the Government of Indonesia achieve its poverty reduction target of 8-10 percent by 2014. Support will include providing the National Team with qualified consultants and assistance to support its analytical and policy functions. The Contractor will primarily play a human resources and logistics support role but will also be required to have technical expertise in the areas of monitoring and evaluation and activity management. AusAID has established an  interim facility  which is currently in place assisting the National Team with office setup and provision of initial staffing resources, until the Facility can be mobilised. It is anticipated that the project will commence in April 2011 and continue over four (4) years.

title: Australia Pacific Technical College - Stage II
desc: The Australia-Pacific Technical College (APTC) was established in July 2007 with Australian Government funding and the backing of the leaders of the Pacific Islands Forum (PIF). The underlying rationale of the APTC is to facilitate regional labour mobility through demand-driven, internationally recognised and portable technical and vocational skills development for the formal wage economy.  The APTC has the goal of increasing the supply of skilled workers in targeted sectors in the Pacific region; improving employment opportunities for Pacific Islanders nationally, regionally and internationally; and increasing productivity. There is a clear strategic role for the APTC in supporting Pacific regionalism and regional market integration, including trade in services (labour mobility) both through regional service delivery and through skills development. Stage I of the APTC, covering four years, is scheduled to conclude in June 2011. APTC Stage II (July 2011-June 2015) will continue operations and provide training in response to industry demands in several existing schools: Automotive, Construction & Electrical and Manufacturing (SACEM), Tourism and Hospitality (STH) and Health and Community Services (SHCS).  The focus is on upgrading skills and providing formal qualifications to students who already have work-experience. Students will enter the APTC as tuition fee-paying, employer/other donor funded or scholarship students. Qualifications will be awarded under the APTC brand.

title: Pacific Region Infrastructure Facility Management Unit
desc: The Pacific Region Infrastructure Facility (PRIF) Management Unit is a multi-donor coordination and financing partnership between AusAID, the New Zealand Aid Program, the Asian Development Bank and the World Bank Group.  The Facility is helping Pacific Island Countries overcome the significant challenges they face in linking people to services and markets.  The Facility will strengthen the quality of support for improved infrastructure and will help Pacific island countries develop and maintain infrastructure for transport, water, sanitation, waste management, energy and communications, in both rural and urban areas.

title: Waste Panel for National Waste Policy Consultancies

title: Industry Profiling and Benefit/Cost Analysis Consultancy Report on Perfluorooctane Sulphonate (PFOS)
desc: The Australian Government, as represented by DSEWPaC, is a Party to the Stockholm Convention, an international treaty on Persistent Organic Pollutants (POPs).  The international Parties agreed in May 2009 to add nine new chemicals to the Convention s Annexes, including perfluorooctane sulfonate (as defined under the Stockholm Convention).     PFOS has been and is currently used by Australian industry. Consultancy services are required: (1) to develop an accurate and up to date profile of the use of PFOS by Australian industry in articles and products and in chemical formulations; (2) to develop in close collaboration with DSEWPaC, feasible domestic implementation options that would meet the obligations under the Convention relating to PFOS use and PFOS-waste and an assessment of their likely efficacy; and (3) a benefit/cost analysis (BCA) of the feasible domestic implementation options that could give effect to obligations under the Stockholm Convention.

title: Examination Facilities, Supervision, and Delivery Services (CyberExams)
desc: CASA has an existing agreement with Assessment Services Pty Limited (ASL) for the provision of Cyberexam services. This existing agreement is set to expire March 2012.  CASA through this Request for Tender (RFT) seeks to tender the Examination Delivery Services for CASA theory examinations utilizing CASA s web-based CyberExams system. This examination system uses the Internet to enable bookings of CASA examinations and to deliver CASA examinations as screen-based examinations to approved centres throughout Australia. The system also provides candidates with examination results and a report on areas of deficient knowledge picked up during scoring of the completed examinations.     The successful tenderer is required to provide the facilities and supervision for the CASA examinations at a minimum of 29 specified locations including cities, major towns, and regional and remote locations within Australia (refer to 3.6). The CASA examinations will be offered between Monday to Friday from 0800 to 1800 local time excluding weekends and public holidays.

title: Interim Governance for Development Support Services in Timor-Leste
desc: INTERIM GOVERNANCE FOR DEVELOPMENT SUPPORT SERVICES IN TIMOR-LESTEThe goal of the Program is for AusAID to work in partnership with the Government of Timor-Leste, to support the Government of Timor-Leste s Strategic Development Plan to:• support the development of good ideas and initiatives for better service-delivery, economic growth, and the creation of jobs and opportunities for better quality of life;• support core policies / systems in budget, financial policy, and economic management, and • support the governments  civil service to better deliver services.The contractor will support AusAID s Public Financial Management and Public Administration team by providing logistical and administrative support associated with an interim program of activities and intended to be rolled into the new Governance for Development Program.  It is anticipated that the program will commence in June 2012 and will continue over 12 months with an option of an up to 6-month extension.    Selection will be on a one step basis.  The closing date for submission of proposals is 2:00pm (Canberra time) Tuesday 13 March 2012.  Tender documents are available on the AusTender website: https://www.tenders.gov.au/   All enquiries should be addressed to:  PAS Officer by email G4DDEPLOYMENTRFT@AusAID.gov.au or facsimile +61 2 6206 4885

category: Pollutants tracking and monitoring and rehabilitation services
title: Testing of Articles for Persistent Organic Pollutants
desc: The Australian Government, as represented by DSEWPaC, is a Party to the Stockholm Convention, an international treaty on Persistent Organic Pollutants (POPs).  Parties to the Convention agreed in May 2009 to add nine new chemicals to the Convention s Annexes, including two brominated flame retardants [tetrabromodiphenyl ether and pentabromodiphenyl ether as contained in commercial pentabromodiphenyl ether (c-pentaBDE) and hexabromodiphenyl ether and heptabromodiphenyl ether as contained in commercial octabromodiphenyl ether (c-octaBDE)] and perfluorooctane sulfonic acid, its salts and perfluorooctane sulfonyl  fluoride (collectively covered by the term PFOS).  The possible presence of these chemicals in articles currently being imported into Australia may have implications for how Australia can meet the requirements of the Convention, should it proceed with ratification.  The Department requires the provision of a research project involving the targeted testing and analysis of articles such as electronic articles, textiles and furnishings that may contain these chemicals. This project is expected to produce results that will help develop and inform decisions on management options for the chemicals.
text: Testing of Articles for Persistent Organic Pollutants.The Australian Government, as represented by DSEWPaC, is a Party to the Stockholm Convention, an international treaty on Persistent Organic Pollutants (POPs).  Parties to the Convention agreed in May 2009 to add nine new chemicals to the Convention s Annexes, including two brominated flame retardants [tetrabromodiphenyl ether and pentabromodiphenyl ether as contained in commercial pentabromodiphenyl ether (c-pentaBDE) and hexabromodiphenyl ether and heptabromodiphenyl ether as contained in commercial octabromodiphenyl ether (c-octaBDE)] and perfluorooctane sulfonic acid, its salts and perfluorooctane sulfonyl  fluoride (collectively covered by the term PFOS).  The possible presence of these chemicals in articles currently being imported into Australia may have implications for how Australia can meet the requirements of the Convention, should it proceed with ratification.  The Department requires the provision of a research project involving the targeted testing and analysis of articles such as electronic articles, textiles and furnishings that may contain these chemicals. This project is expected to produce results that will help develop and inform decisions on management options for the chemicals.

title: Australia s Education Partnership with Indonesia - Education Partnership Outreach Services (EPOS)
desc: Australia s Education Partnership with Indonesia - Education Partnership Outreach Services.  The Government of Australia and Indonesia are entering into a new AUD500m Education Partnership. The Partnership will focus on four components: school construction, school and district management, Islamic school accreditation, and the Analytical and Capacity Development Partnership. The Education Partnership is Australia s contribution to Indonesia s Education Sector Support Program, which is also co-financed by the European Union.  The Education Partnership Outreach Services (EPOS) Contractor will operate across the four components of the Education Partnership and will be responsible for managing and implementing the Education Partnership s public diplomacy strategy and outreach program.

title: BUILDING THE RESILIENCE AND AWARENESS OF METRO MANILA COMMUNITIES TO NATURAL DISASTER AND CLIMATE CHANGE IMPACTS
desc: Building the Resilience and Awareness of Metron Manila Communities to Natural Disaster and Climate Change Impact (BRACE)  The Governments of Australia and the Philippines have mutually agreed that disaster risk reduction and climate change adaptation should be a key focus of Australia s aid program in the Philippines.      The BRACE Program will contribute to strengthening the resilience of highly vulnerable cities in Metropolitan Manila to the risks of natural disasters and the changing climate.  Its four components provide a package of practical measures to prepare and protect communities:  i) Hazard and Disaster Risk Analysis ii) Community-Based Disaster Risk Management  iii) Comprehensive Land Use Planning and iv) Building Safer Settlements.

title: Australia Mekong NGO Engagement Platform (AMNEP)
desc: MEKONG: NGO engagement administrative support unit  AusAID is seeking to enhance the way it and its NGO partners work together in Cambodia, Laos and Vietnam to better achieve shared development goals.  Central to this will be the closer integration of NGO policy dialogue and activity into AusAID s broader engagement strategies in these countries.     The Australia Mekong-Non Government Organisation Engagement Platform (AM-NEP) will support this new way of working by providing regional resources to strengthen the quality of AusAID s NGO engagement including:  forums for regional dialogue with NGO partners; policy and technical expertise to strengthen strategy and activity designs; support to promote monitoring, evaluation and lesson sharing; and administrative support.       The Administrative Support Unit (ASU) of AM-NEP, the subject of this tender, will facilitate the provision of these services to AusAID Mekong programs and partner NGOs.

title: Management of Transport Sector Support Program Phase 2 (PNG)
desc: PNG: Transport Sector Support Program (Phase 2): Procurement of Implementing Service Provider  Well-planned and maintained transport infrastructure underpins steady economic growth and supports resources development. Australia recognises that it will take time to achieve PNG s transport related development goals and has made a long term commitment (15 to 20 years) to support the Government of Papua New Guinea in its endeavors to achieve a well maintained transport infrastructure network. This long term commitment is embodied in the PNG-Australia Transport Sector Support Program (TSSP) which was established in 2007. TSSP is nearing the end of its first phase and will shortly evolve into the second phase.

title: Information and Telecommunication Technology Training Services
desc: The Commonwealth has an ongoing requirement to provide Information and Telecommunications Technology Training courses to staff within ASD. ASD s communications environment is changing dramatically and with these changes a heavy reliance on networking knowledge and skills is required. The ASD Academy does not have the resources to meet this demand so will contract networking courses to ensure the delivery of high quality networking training from entry level to advanced digital network intelligence.  Due to the changing environment and the increased need for more in-depth technical networking knowledge, ASD has a requirement to expand the scope of the training provided to include flexible learning options such as e-learning and practical application of this training to work related situations and problems. This work will require the redevelopment of some existing courses as well as developing and delivering new courses.
text: Information and Telecommunication Technology Training Services. The Commonwealth has an ongoing requirement to provide Information and Telecommunications Technology Training courses to staff within ASD. ASD s communications environment is changing dramatically and with these changes a heavy reliance on networking knowledge and skills is required. The ASD Academy does not have the resources to meet this demand so will contract networking courses to ensure the delivery of high quality networking training from entry level to advanced digital network intelligence.  Due to the changing environment and the increased need for more in-depth technical networking knowledge, ASD has a requirement to expand the scope of the training provided to include flexible learning options such as e-learning and practical application of this training to work related situations and problems. This work will require the redevelopment of some existing courses as well as developing and delivering new courses.

title: Naval Shipbuilding College
desc: Respondents are invited to submit a proposal to support the development and delivery of a Naval Shipbuilding College (NSC) to facilitate the delivery of the workforce outcomes required to build and sustain Australia s naval shipbuilding endeavour, as outlined in the Naval Shipbuilding Plan, released by the Government on 16 May 2017.  Over the next ten (10) to fifteen (15) years, the size and skill level of the naval shipbuilding and sustainment workforce will need to increase significantly to meet the demands created by the Government s planned investments in naval shipbuilding.  The naval shipbuilding enterprise is too important for the market forces of supply and demand to manage growth and skilling requirements. A national approach to rebuilding the naval shipbuilding and sustainment workforce is required. On 24 March 2017, the Minister for Defence Industry, the Hon Christopher Pyne MP announced that the Government will establish a Naval Shipbuilding College to identify, train and retain workers for the naval shipbuilding enterprise.  The NSC project is expected to be delivered through three phases, with progress to the next phase dependent on the successful achievement of the previous phase:• the first phase will commence in 2018 and focus on establishing the NSC; is expected to build capacity and annual throughput at existing education and training institutions across Australia, in key entry level trade qualifications. It will commence a nation-wide communication program, including a career awareness program for school level audiences and workers in adjacent industries; and create a workforce register;• the second phase of the Naval Shipbuilding College is expected to commence in 2020/21. The College will continue to increase capacity and student throughput in key entry-level trades, and will build on this to also achieve increased capacity and throughput in key higher education qualifications (such as naval architecture/engineering) from universities; and• the final phase of the NSC Project could commence from around 2022-2023, subject to successful implementation of the first two phases, and is to develop and construct a purpose-built Naval Shipbuilding College training facility located at the Osborne Naval Shipyard that will offer a range of naval shipbuilding and sustainment education and training that cannot be met from existing institutions.  To support the establishment and delivery of the NSC, the Commonwealth, through the Defence of Defence, is seeking to engage with the broader training and education industry and with potential NSC providers to:• provide informed input and innovative ideas that can be considered by the Commonwealth in determining the optimal service development and delivery solution for the NSC; and• enable an industry partner or partners to be selected to deliver the first two phases of NSC outcomes.

title: Principals as STEM Leaders – Building the Evidence Base to Improve Stem Learning
desc: The research project has three workstreams.  Workstream One – Research (including identifying best practice STEM leadership approaches) to inform development of professional learning modules/resources and a supporting mentoring approach for principals as STEM leaders.  Workstream Two – Develop and pilot the professional learning modules and mentoring resources in this research project.  Workstream Three – Over the life of the research project, monitor and evaluate the resources and supporting mentoring model developed under the research project to:a. determine those best practice approaches that increase principals  STEM capabilities;b. result in high quality and accessible resources being available at the end of the research project.

title: SMART Surveillance for pests, diseases and weeds
desc: GRDC relies on periodic economic surveys on the costs of disease, weeds and invertebrate pests when making investment decisions. GRDC needs better information to support a seasonal or twice seasonal situation analysis on biotic threats to improve investment decisions and to alert growers to changes in abundance of current threats or movement of new threats into different regions, or changes in biology of weeds pests or diseases or increased resistance of these threats. The development of new tools for trapping biotic threats will assist in providing some of this data for pests and disease but not weeds. The grains industry has a high adoption of agronomic consultants, and the use of electronic recording platforms (both commercial agronomists and growers).  The utilisation of this rich source of biotic threat information has not been attempted. This investment is to scope the feasibility of integrating the skills of agronomists and/or the records they or grower keep to provide a more detailed picture of the current distribution and abundance of biotic threats. Integration of these data could lead to: the provision of improved pest alerts to growers; determination of changes in species abundance and temporal activity; warnings of the appearance of new biotic threats; development of resistance and management options being implemented by growers.

category: Crop production and management and protection
title: National Canola Pathology Program – epidemiology, surveillance and management strategies
desc: The Australian canola industry has produced on average 3.5 million tonnes annually over the past 5 years, with exports alone resulting in $1.6 billion annually. In addition to direct profits from canola production, canola is an essential part of the cropping system, providing significant and reliable yield benefits through the control of diseases and weeds for subsequent cereal crops. The projection for the Australian canola industry is to produce 6.1 million tonnes per year by 2025 (Australian Oilseeds Federation). Some of the main limitations to this expansion and threats to the canola industry are from diseases, especially those caused by fungi. Without the continual control of diseases such as blackleg and sclerotinia stem rot, the canola industry cannot be sustainable or profitable. Furthermore, with the continual expansion of the canola industry the impact of these diseases will only increase due to the intensification of rotations and greater amounts of disease inoculum. The total estimated area planted with canola in 2016 was 615,661 hectares (Northern region), 654,023 hectares (Southern region) and 2,541,302 hectares (Western region) with an average of at least 50% of this being impacted by diseases particularly in the medium-high rainfall zones. The price per tonne in 2016/2017 was $520 and the yield was estimated at 1.4 tonnes per hectare averaged across all regions. With 15% diseases impact, the cost to the industry was over $200M. The aim of this research is to further develop the existing national canola pathology program to maintain the profitability of the canola industry. The project will monitor all diseases of canola and provide information to farmers regarding management of these diseases and risk of yield loss ensuring enduring profitability to the Australian canola growers.

title: Using seasonal forecast information and tools to manage risk and increase profitability in the Southern Region
desc: GRDC invites tenders from suitable contractor(s) to establish a participatory pilot program to develop and promote tools to better use Bureau of Meteorology weather data and seasonal outlook forecasts.  A small group of advisors will be up-skilled and their knowledge and experiences used to better understand the implications of seasonal forecasts and strategies to manage risk and increase profitability.  The information generated from the program will enable the development of guidelines and  rules of thumb . It is expected that this investment will draw upon and add value to existing related investments including the outcomes of the Managing Climate Variability R&D Program and the Forewarned is forearmed: equipping farmers and agricultural value chains to proactively manage the impacts of extreme climate events Rural R&D for Profit investment.   This proposed investment would be undertaken over a two-year period from 1 March 2018 to 29 February 2020 and will be delivered across the GRDC Southern Region.

category: Crop production and management and protection
title: Development of local strategies to enable the integrated & profitable management of Annual ryegrass seed banks in HRZ
desc: GRDC invites tenders from suitable contractor(s) for that this investment will involve a number of large scale replicated demonstration trials to validate the economic benefit of different weed control tactics when integrated into various locally relevant best management programs. This may include a comparison of grower standard practice with a  take-no-prisoners  approach; a tactical strategy responsive to seasonal conditions; and a  best-bet  strategy. The investment will utilise a series of demonstration trials, extension and communication activities to build upon the extensive historic and current R,D&E undertaken in the area of weed management. The project will utilise existing information generated from GRDC investments including Weed management in the southern region mixed farming systems - strategies to combat herbicide resistance, Harvest Weed Seed Control (HWSC), Stubble Initiative, Pastures in crop sequencing and others.  It is also expected that the delivery of this investment will complement and value-add to the GRDC Cultural Weed Management investment.  This proposed investment would be undertaken over a two-year period, commencing from March 01, 2018 and concluding on May 29, 2020, and will be delivered across the major grain growing areas of the high rainfall districts of the GRDC Southern Region.

category: Crop production and management and protection
title: Assessing the economic value of precision agricultural tools for grain farming businesses in the Southern Region
desc: GRDC invites tenders from suitable contractor(s) to provide growers and advisers in the southern region with enhanced capacity and skills to assess the economic impact of the adoption of various precision agriculture (PA) technologies in order to make informed business decisions. This will be achieved by identifying key technologies and situations where PA has been proven to consistently improve the profitability of cropping systems; developing a simple decision matrix and related tools to support PA decision making; producing relevant high impact communications and extension activities to promote awareness and build the skills, knowledge and confidence to motivate growers and advisers to realise the profitability opportunities presented by the broader adoption of PA in the GRDC Southern region.  This proposed investment would be undertaken over a two-year period from 1 March 2018 to 29 February 2020 and will be delivered across the GRDC Southern Region.

desc: GRDC invites tenders from suitable contractor(s) to provide growers and advisers across the GRDC Southern Region with information and tools to identify opportunities and strategies to better integrate cropping and livestock enterprises and increase the profitability and resilience of the whole farm business. category: Crop production and management and protection
title: Sustainable use of insecticides & on-farm implementation of integrated pest management strategies in the Southern region
desc: GRDC invites tenders from suitable contractor(s) to develop, promote and deliver a number of high impact communication products and extension activities to raise awareness and build knowledge relating to the risk, occurrence, impact and management of insecticide resistance. This investment should support practice change required to increase the incidence and extent of adoption of sustainable and cost-effective integrated pest management strategies tailored to local farming systems and environment for key insect pests of grain crops in the GRDC Southern Region. Activities must address the current attitudes of growers, advisors and agribusiness and aim to motivate them to implement best practice IPM strategies on-farm.  This proposed investment would be undertaken over a two-year period from 1 May 2018 to 30 April 2020 and will be delivered across the GRDC Southern Region.

category: Crop production and management and protection
title: Increasing N fixation in pulse crops through improved rhizobia, inoculation and crop management practices
desc: The GRDC seeks to enhance nitrogen (N) fixation of winter pulse crops through improved rhizobial strains for hostile soils and enhanced inoculation practices that minimise the potential impact of fertiliser and crop protection applications, and maximise rhizobial survival, nodulation and nodule function. These improvements will broaden the adaptation of pulses onto soil types and areas where they are currently not widely cultivated. This three year R&D investment, starting early 2018, will be supported by a separate extension and communication investment to promote awareness of nodulation and N fixation in pulses, and adoption of best inoculation practices.

title: Improving the profitability of pulse production through local validation of research outcomes in the Southern Region
desc: GRDC invites tenders from applicants to undertake a targeted validation trial program of significant scale to deliver local data and knowledge for the development of pulse crops suitable to areas across the southern region where research and development is limited. In collaboration with the Southern Pulse Agronomy project (DAV00150), pulse crops and constraints need to be prioritised for each agro-ecological zone to develop the focus of the validation program. For example, it is envisaged that up to four of the most important pulse crops and up to four constraints will be examined in each zone where gaps exist. Local biophysical data from the validation trials and their impact on crop management, farming systems and farm economics will be made publicly available. The validation trial data will feed back into research and development activities of the Southern Pulse Agronomy project, and new knowledge will flow into the pulse extension project (PROC 9175825). In partnership with these and other GRDC projects, this three and a half year investment, starting early 2018, will deliver greater knowledge of the pulse phenotypes suited to each agro-ecological zone and management practices to optimise their production and profitability.  This proposed investment would be undertaken over a period from 30 March 2018 to 1 May 2021 and will be delivered across the GRDC Southern Region.

title: Optimising mungbean yields - Project B - Improving mungbean irrigation management
desc: By 2023 growers across the northern grains region have the knowledge and tools to achieve consistent mungbean yields.  The project will use a combination of surveys, glasshouse and field trial data to:    Generate a greater understanding of environmental covariates that explain yield stability;  Underpin an improved ability to model GxExM interactions in mungbean;  Provide clearly defined management strategies to address the yield gap in mungbeans and;  Improve grower confidence to variability and risk in mungbean production.

title: Using soil & plant testing data to better inform nutrient management & optimise fertiliser investments for grain growers
desc: GRDC invites tenders from suitable applicants to provide grain growers in the GRDC Southern region with evidence of the usefulness and economic value of well-informed fertiliser decisions, to influence their attitudes and motivation to adopt improved nutrient management techniques. This will be achieved by working directly with growers, FERTCARE accredited advisors and industry across the southern region to demonstrate the process and benefits of soil and plant testing, and improved crop nutrition advice across two seasons. An economic framework will be developed to quantify the likely returns from improved nutrient management techniques and the opportunity to boost farm profit, and these findings will be extended to other growers not directly involved in the demonstration program. The large numbers of soil profile analyses collected by the demonstration program (about 7,000 p.a.) will also provide a useful snapshot of nutrient status and soil fertility in these states, and could be used to highlight emerging issues like soil acidity and declining organic matter.  This proposed investment would be undertaken from 30 May 2018 to 30 June 2021 and will be delivered across the GRDC Southern Region.

category: Crop production and management and protection
title: Improved grower and advisor awareness and knowledge of pulse N fixation and inoculation practices in the Southern region
desc: This three year communication and extension focused investment aims to extend research outcomes in a practical and applied manner, utilising a range of approaches to realise on-farm impact of related investments in R&D, subsequently improving crop nodulation, N fixation and grain legume yields across the GRDC southern region. The investment will increase awareness and build knowledge of growers and advisors concerning commercial inoculant types, formulations and inoculation techniques, and develop their skills regarding the monitoring and assessment of legume nodulation, and mitigation of any possible impacts of crop protection products and fertiliser treatments on rhizobia survival and effectiveness.  This proposed investment would be undertaken over a three-year period from 30 May 2018 to 30 June 20121 and will be delivered across the GRDC Southern Region.

title: Management of Sclerotinia in farming systems
desc: By 2025, 50% of grain growers who adopt an integrated approach for the management of Sclerotinia across their farming system will decrease crop losses due to this disease by 20% per annum. Additionally, the adoption of Integrated Disease Management for Sclerotinia will allow for greater adoption of crop diversification, including maintenance or growth in pulse crops within the farming systems.

title: Management of Alice Springs Satellite Ground Station (ASSGS) As A Service
desc: Geoscience Australia is seeking to appoint a Contractor to manage the ASSGS as a service under Contract for a period of 10 years with a possible extension exercisable by GA of 5 years.     Under the  requirement:    the Contractor becomes a provider of fee-for-service to GA as well as to potentially other public entities and the private sector (subject at all times to CAT and GA s prior approval);      the Contractor will have to comply with International Traffic in Arms Regulations (ITAR) and obtain all other Approvals if required to do so.       the Contractor shall be responsible for the day-to-day operations and ongoing support of the ASSGS, including preventative and corrective maintenance and upgrades. All preventative and corrective maintenance and upgrades are to be funded and implemented by the Contractor, subject to GA approval;      the Contractor is permitted, subject to GA s approval in accordance with the Contract, to contract with other commercial entities and make necessary upgrades to ASSGS for the provision of products and services to customers other than GA without impeding on or adversely affecting GA s operational priorities;      the Contractor shall assist GA with increasing the importance of, and strengthening the role played by GA in the international Landsat Ground Network (LGN) community;      the Contractor shall undertake key projects to identify and address technical and regulatory tion (ASSGS) As A Service barriers, which are impeding Australian space industry s ability to take advantage of key opportunities;      GA becomes a fee-paying customer in accordance with the Contract with enforceable Service Levels against the Contractor for the acquisition of required data and operational services, as laid out in Section 2.03 (b);      GA retains the unencumbered ownership of the ASSGS including all major spares,  upgrades and enhancements done to the ASSGS Facilities and Systems by the Contractor;      GA retains absolute operational priority for satellite passes of interest to the Commonwealth government and its allies; and    GA retains absolute operational priority for satellite passes in the event of scheduling conflicts, emergency management situations and other specific circumstances determined by GA.

title: Services for the organisation of the National Schools Constitutional Convention 2019-2021
desc: a. The Supplier must undertake the Services: to the highest ethical standards; fairly; effectively; impartially; courteously to the Australian public; and with sensitivity to the diversity of the Australian public;  b. The Supplier must establish a feedback and complaints process to deal with feedback and complaints from recipients of the Services about the Supplier s delivery of the Services. The Supplier must consult ansd co-operate with the Customer on the development of this process.  c. The Supplier s feedback and complaints process must:  i. be consistent with this contract; ii. clearly indicate that recipients of the Services may also provide feedback or complaint directly to the Customer using the Customer s contact information provided to the Supplier;iii. be underpinned by principles of fairness, accessibility, responsiveness, efficiency and integration;iv. be developed and implemented, as far as possible, based on the Commonwealth Ombudsman s Better Practice Guide to Complaint Handling (http://www.ombudsman.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0020/35615/Better-practice-guide-to-complaint-handling.pdf).  d. Upon request, the Supplier must give the Customer details of the feedback and complaints process the Supplier has established.  e. The Supplier must publicise to recipients of the Services the existence and details of the feedback and complaints process.  f. The Supplier must keep a feedback and complaints register which includes, but is not limited to, details about:  i. all feedback and complaints received by the Supplier;ii. all feedback and complaints referred to the Supplier by, or through, the Customer; andiii. the Personnel and subcontractors (if any) the subject of the feedback or complaint, circumstances giving rise to the feedback or complaint, the investigation undertaken (where relevant), and any follow-up action.
